WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:06.480
<v Speaker 1>So we saw that we can use the present tense to refer to the future.

00:00:06.480 --> 00:00:10.240
<v Speaker 1>For example, if we have some future context.

00:00:10.379 --> 00:00:13.340
<v Speaker 1>We can just use the present tense by itself.

00:00:13.340 --> 00:00:18.140
<v Speaker 1>So we could say I am having breakfast.

00:00:18.380 --> 00:00:20.380
<v Speaker 1>with them tomorrow.

00:00:20.380 --> 00:00:24.460
<v Speaker 1>Now in Spanish you don't say with them, you say with they.

00:00:24.460 --> 00:00:25.260
<v Speaker 1>With they.

00:00:25.260 --> 00:00:27.099
<v Speaker 1>So how would that be first?

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:28.600
<v Speaker 2>Con ellos.

00:00:28.600 --> 00:00:29.000
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.279
<v Speaker 1>And to have breakfast we said was to unfast.

00:00:33.720 --> 00:00:37.320
<v Speaker 1>Like in English breakfast, break, fast.

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:41.320
<v Speaker 1>So I'm having breakfast with them tomorrow.

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:46.320
<v Speaker 2>Desayuno con ellos manana.

00:00:49.760 --> 00:00:58.719
<v Speaker 1>And if we don't have a future context, like manana or any other context that's showing us is the future, we can also use I am going.

00:00:58.520 --> 00:01:00.440
<v Speaker 1>to speak about the future.

00:01:00.440 --> 00:01:04.199
<v Speaker 1>So you can say I am going to have breakfast with them.

00:01:04.199 --> 00:01:05.400
<v Speaker 1>How is that?

00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:11.799
<v Speaker 2>Voy a desayunar con ellos.

00:01:13.320 --> 00:01:15.399
<v Speaker 1>Voy a desayunar con ellos.

00:01:15.399 --> 00:01:16.360
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:20.880
<v Speaker 1>And if we had the future context, it doesn't mean we have to say desayuno con ellos mañana.

00:01:20.880 --> 00:01:24.000
<v Speaker 1>We could also say boy a desayunar con ellos mañana.

00:01:24.159 --> 00:01:28.400
<v Speaker 1>The fact that we have future context doesn't mean we can't use boy anymore.

00:01:28.040 --> 00:01:33.320
<v Speaker 1>So we've seen in that way we can use the present to talk about the future.

00:01:33.320 --> 00:01:36.280
<v Speaker 1>But this doesn't mean that we don't have a future tense in Spanish.

00:01:36.280 --> 00:01:37.080
<v Speaker 1>We do.

00:01:37.080 --> 00:01:40.680
<v Speaker 1>Luckily, we don't have to learn any new sounds

00:01:40.840 --> 00:01:43.479
<v Speaker 1>To master the future tense in Spanish.

00:01:43.479 --> 00:01:50.520
<v Speaker 1>The future tense in Spanish is connected with the past tense that we learn of haber.

00:01:51.120 --> 00:01:58.240
<v Speaker 1>This past of I have had breakfast or I have eaten, I have gone.

00:01:58.240 --> 00:02:01.760
<v Speaker 1>So let's make a recap of the forms of Aber.

00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:12.920
<v Speaker 1>Now it's very irregular and we said that a nice trick to remember the different forms of aber is just looking at the two vowel sounds inside the verb aber.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:15.560
<v Speaker 1>So what are those two vowel sounds?

00:02:15.740 --> 00:02:17.260
<v Speaker 2>A and E.

00:02:17.260 --> 00:02:17.740
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:17.740 --> 00:02:19.020
<v Speaker 1>Let's start with E.

00:02:19.020 --> 00:02:21.580
<v Speaker 1>What does E mean by itself?

00:02:21.900 --> 00:02:22.940
<v Speaker 2>I have.

00:02:22.940 --> 00:02:23.660
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:23.660 --> 00:02:26.140
<v Speaker 1>I have spelled H E.

00:02:25.760 --> 00:02:28.160
<v Speaker 1>And what other person is connected with I?

00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:31.120
<v Speaker 1>What's the plural of I, let's say?

00:02:31.120 --> 00:02:32.080
<v Speaker 2>EMOS.

00:02:32.080 --> 00:02:32.480
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:32.480 --> 00:02:33.040
<v Speaker 1>We.

00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:36.000
<v Speaker 1>So we have A for I have and EMOS for we have.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:37.760
<v Speaker 1>What is a by itself?

00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:40.400
<v Speaker 1>H A.

00:02:40.100 --> 00:02:45.220
<v Speaker 2>He sh he she it or you formal.

00:02:45.220 --> 00:02:45.780
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:45.780 --> 00:02:48.100
<v Speaker 1>So give me the other two versions now

00:02:49.300 --> 00:02:50.180
<v Speaker 2>An.

00:02:50.180 --> 00:02:50.740
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:50.740 --> 00:02:51.860
<v Speaker 1>They or you guys.

00:02:51.860 --> 00:02:53.220
<v Speaker 2>Or you, yeah.

00:02:53.540 --> 00:02:57.060
<v Speaker 2>And us, which is you informal.

00:02:57.060 --> 00:02:58.020
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:57.400 --> 00:02:58.840
<v Speaker 1>So that's our set.

00:02:58.840 --> 00:03:04.360
<v Speaker 1>Let's practice a little bit some structures with Aber just to recap.

00:03:04.360 --> 00:03:07.879
<v Speaker 1>So what was to sleep?

00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:09.640
<v Speaker 1>Torment.

00:03:09.640 --> 00:03:10.440
<v Speaker 1>Dormir.

00:03:10.440 --> 00:03:10.760
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:10.760 --> 00:03:12.520
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say I have slept?

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:15.000
<v Speaker 1>Begin with I have.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:15.880
<v Speaker 2>Eh.

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:16.760
<v Speaker 2>Dormido.

00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:17.160
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:18.920
<v Speaker 1>We have slept.

00:03:21.340 --> 00:03:23.739
<v Speaker 1>He has slept.

00:03:23.739 --> 00:03:25.099
<v Speaker 2>A dormido.

00:03:25.099 --> 00:03:25.580
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:25.580 --> 00:03:28.060
<v Speaker 1>How would you say to recommend?

00:03:28.660 --> 00:03:30.340
<v Speaker 2>Recommendacion.

00:03:30.340 --> 00:03:31.379
<v Speaker 2>Recommendar.

00:03:31.379 --> 00:03:31.780
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:31.780 --> 00:03:35.300
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say they have recommended it?

00:03:35.300 --> 00:03:37.140
<v Speaker 1>They have recommended it.

00:03:36.700 --> 00:03:41.420
<v Speaker 1>And I remind you that with these structures with Aber, the it has to come before Aber.

00:03:41.420 --> 00:03:43.420
<v Speaker 1>There's no option of where to put it.

00:03:43.420 --> 00:03:45.099
<v Speaker 1>So they have recommended it

00:03:46.920 --> 00:03:49.800
<v Speaker 2>Lo han recomendado.

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:51.480
<v Speaker 1>Lo an recomendado.

00:03:51.480 --> 00:03:52.200
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:52.200 --> 00:03:54.440
<v Speaker 1>So these forms that we have

00:03:54.740 --> 00:04:05.140
<v Speaker 1>These forms of aber that we have, e-emos, a-as, an, are also the endings that we have for the future tense.

00:04:04.760 --> 00:04:10.040
<v Speaker 1>So like I said, we will learn the future tense now without having to learn any new sounds.

00:04:10.040 --> 00:04:12.840
<v Speaker 1>Now the interesting thing about the future tense.

00:04:12.940 --> 00:04:24.780
<v Speaker 1>is that we take the verb in its two form, whether it's an R verb, er verb or ear verb, doesn't matter, and we put the ending at the end of the two form and we stress the ending.

00:04:24.780 --> 00:04:27.020
<v Speaker 1>We are effectively pushing

00:04:27.520 --> 00:04:30.640
<v Speaker 1>the accent into the future.

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:35.920
<v Speaker 1>For example, we have comer, and what was I have from Aber?

00:04:35.740 --> 00:04:36.380
<v Speaker 2>Eh.

00:04:36.380 --> 00:04:36.860
<v Speaker 1>Eh.

00:04:36.860 --> 00:04:39.500
<v Speaker 1>So that's the sound without the H, just the sound.

00:04:40.220 --> 00:04:44.300
<v Speaker 1>That's the sound that we need for future for I.

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:47.760
<v Speaker 1>We add that on to comer and we get komere.

00:04:47.760 --> 00:04:51.120
<v Speaker 1>And that's I will eat.

00:04:51.120 --> 00:04:51.920
<v Speaker 1>Now we are

00:04:52.240 --> 00:05:00.560
<v Speaker 1>Pushing the accent into the future, which might just seem like a coincidence, but you can notice that it happens in other languages as well, this phenomenon.

00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:03.920
<v Speaker 1>For example, in Greek, part of the past tense

00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:09.460
<v Speaker 1>is to pull the accent back, one syllable, to pull the accent back into the past.

00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:17.220
<v Speaker 1>And actually this is so important in Greek that if there is not a syllable there to do it, you add one to pull the accent back.

00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:17.960
<v Speaker 1>into the past.

00:05:17.960 --> 00:05:29.880
<v Speaker 1>So this is a phenomenon that you see in in different languages, the accents representing somehow or reflecting somehow the concept of time and tenses.

00:05:29.300 --> 00:05:33.860
<v Speaker 1>So here we are pushing the accent into the future, komere.

00:05:33.860 --> 00:05:35.139
<v Speaker 1>I will eat.

00:05:35.379 --> 00:05:39.620
<v Speaker 1>You can give me the rest of the versions for the future of comer.

00:05:40.420 --> 00:05:41.620
<v Speaker 1>Comeremos.

00:05:41.620 --> 00:05:42.020
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:42.020 --> 00:05:42.980
<v Speaker 1>Comeremos.

00:05:42.980 --> 00:05:44.260
<v Speaker 1>We will eat.

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:45.220
<v Speaker 2>Comera.

00:05:45.220 --> 00:05:45.700
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:45.700 --> 00:05:46.740
<v Speaker 1>He will eat.

00:05:46.740 --> 00:05:47.620
<v Speaker 1>Comeras.

00:05:47.860 --> 00:05:50.100
<v Speaker 1>You in fumel will eat.

00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:50.960
<v Speaker 1>Comeran.

00:05:50.960 --> 00:05:51.520
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:51.520 --> 00:05:53.440
<v Speaker 1>They or you guys relate.

00:05:53.520 --> 00:05:54.160
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:54.160 --> 00:05:55.600
<v Speaker 1>What was to go?

00:05:55.760 --> 00:05:57.440
<v Speaker 1>We said it was very irregular.

00:05:57.440 --> 00:06:02.800
<v Speaker 1>We have boy and bamos and ba, but the verb to go doesn't look anything like them.

00:06:03.260 --> 00:06:04.060
<v Speaker 1>ER.

00:06:04.060 --> 00:06:05.100
<v Speaker 1>Ear.

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:07.660
<v Speaker 1>Ear in the future is regular.

00:06:07.660 --> 00:06:12.860
<v Speaker 1>So we can follow these rules and get the future tenses of to go.

00:06:12.860 --> 00:06:14.620
<v Speaker 1>I will go, he will go.

00:06:14.620 --> 00:06:16.940
<v Speaker 1>So what is I will go?

00:06:17.840 --> 00:06:30.319
<v Speaker 1>Ire and we will go iremos iremos he will go ira they or you guys

00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:32.020
<v Speaker 1>Iran.

00:06:32.020 --> 00:06:32.740
<v Speaker 1>Iran.

00:06:32.740 --> 00:06:34.020
<v Speaker 1>Like the country.

00:06:34.020 --> 00:06:35.860
<v Speaker 1>They will go to Iran.

00:06:36.980 --> 00:06:38.340
<v Speaker 1>Iran a Iran.

00:06:38.340 --> 00:06:39.620
<v Speaker 1>Iran a Iran.

00:06:39.620 --> 00:06:40.180
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:40.180 --> 00:06:42.100
<v Speaker 1>You in Fumul will go

00:06:43.240 --> 00:06:44.120
<v Speaker 1>Hira.

00:06:44.120 --> 00:06:44.440
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:44.440 --> 00:06:46.280
<v Speaker 1>And what if we wanted to make it a question?

00:06:46.280 --> 00:06:48.120
<v Speaker 1>Will you go?

00:06:48.280 --> 00:06:49.080
<v Speaker 2>Iraz?

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:49.720
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:49.720 --> 00:06:51.160
<v Speaker 1>Won't you go?

00:06:52.620 --> 00:06:54.380
<v Speaker 1>Why won't you go?

00:06:55.660 --> 00:06:56.380
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:56.380 --> 00:06:59.660
<v Speaker 1>What was to find or to encounter?

00:07:02.700 --> 00:07:03.980
<v Speaker 1>I will find

00:07:04.740 --> 00:07:06.020
<v Speaker 1>Encontrare.

00:07:06.020 --> 00:07:06.580
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:07:06.580 --> 00:07:07.700
<v Speaker 1>Encontrare.

00:07:07.700 --> 00:07:10.020
<v Speaker 1>I will find it.

00:07:10.340 --> 00:07:12.020
<v Speaker 2>Lo encontrare.

00:07:12.020 --> 00:07:12.580
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:07:12.580 --> 00:07:14.740
<v Speaker 1>Lo encontrare.

00:07:15.060 --> 00:07:16.740
<v Speaker 1>We will find it.

00:07:17.699 --> 00:07:19.620
<v Speaker 2>Los encontraré.

00:07:19.620 --> 00:07:21.380
<v Speaker 1>That was an interesting era.

00:07:21.380 --> 00:07:28.340
<v Speaker 1>Because I said we, so I made I plural with we and your mind made the it plural, huh?

00:07:28.660 --> 00:07:29.300
<v Speaker 2>Yeah.

00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:31.460
<v Speaker 1>We will find it.

00:07:32.220 --> 00:07:34.300
<v Speaker 2>Lo encontraremos.

00:07:34.300 --> 00:07:34.780
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:07:34.780 --> 00:07:36.860
<v Speaker 1>Lo encontraremos.

00:07:36.860 --> 00:07:40.220
<v Speaker 1>He or she or you fummel will find it.

00:07:41.620 --> 00:07:43.860
<v Speaker 2>Lo encontrara.

00:07:43.860 --> 00:07:44.500
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:07:44.500 --> 00:07:46.740
<v Speaker 1>Lo encontrara.

00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:51.380
<v Speaker 1>He will find them or she will find them or you fumel will find them.

00:07:52.199 --> 00:07:54.600
<v Speaker 1>Los encontrarán.

00:07:54.600 --> 00:07:58.280
<v Speaker 1>So you made both of them them or they.

00:07:58.280 --> 00:07:59.320
<v Speaker 2>You said them.

00:07:59.320 --> 00:08:03.160
<v Speaker 1>But we said he will find them or she will find them.

00:08:03.639 --> 00:08:03.960
<v Speaker 2>Los

00:08:04.680 --> 00:08:05.960
<v Speaker 2>Encontrará.

00:08:05.960 --> 00:08:06.440
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:08:06.440 --> 00:08:08.280
<v Speaker 1>Los encontrará.

00:08:08.280 --> 00:08:11.160
<v Speaker 1>So we want to think about the two things separately, huh?

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:13.800
<v Speaker 1>The who is doing the verb and who are they doing it to?

00:08:13.800 --> 00:08:15.720
<v Speaker 1>Who or what are they doing it to

00:08:15.860 --> 00:08:24.420
<v Speaker 1>We said that kedar means to remain, kedar, and to get the meaning of I stay, we say I remain myself.

00:08:24.420 --> 00:08:25.620
<v Speaker 1>How was that?

00:08:25.620 --> 00:08:27.300
<v Speaker 1>I remain myself

00:08:28.140 --> 00:08:29.180
<v Speaker 2>Mekedo.

00:08:29.180 --> 00:08:30.220
<v Speaker 1>Mekedo.

00:08:30.220 --> 00:08:31.100
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:08:31.100 --> 00:08:33.820
<v Speaker 1>How would you say I will stay then?

00:08:33.820 --> 00:08:36.219
<v Speaker 1>I will remain myself.

00:08:38.040 --> 00:08:40.440
<v Speaker 1>Good, but quedare means I will remain.

00:08:40.440 --> 00:08:44.040
<v Speaker 1>And if you want the meaning of stay, you must must use me.

00:08:44.040 --> 00:08:44.360
<v Speaker 1>Yeah.

00:08:44.360 --> 00:08:45.400
<v Speaker 2>Me quedare.

00:08:45.400 --> 00:08:46.520
<v Speaker 1>Me quedare.

00:08:46.520 --> 00:08:48.520
<v Speaker 1>I will remain myself or I will stay.

00:08:48.520 --> 00:08:50.200
<v Speaker 1>I will stay here.

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:52.560
<v Speaker 2>Me quedare aquí.

00:08:52.560 --> 00:08:53.040
<v Speaker 2>Good.

00:08:53.040 --> 00:08:54.720
<v Speaker 1>What was to prepare?

00:08:54.960 --> 00:08:56.000
<v Speaker 2>Preparar.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:56.480
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:08:56.480 --> 00:08:58.080
<v Speaker 1>And I will prepare

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:00.480
<v Speaker 2>Preparare.

00:09:00.480 --> 00:09:01.120
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:09:01.120 --> 00:09:04.800
<v Speaker 1>So it's very important to think out the whole verb preparare.

00:09:04.800 --> 00:09:07.600
<v Speaker 1>And then add on the e preparare.

00:09:07.360 --> 00:09:16.320
<v Speaker 1>Because a very common mistake that that learners make is to say bre pare and they miss out the last R because they don't think out the whole verb first.

00:09:16.060 --> 00:09:20.940
<v Speaker 1>So we must think out the whole verb first, preparar, and then add on the ending.

00:09:20.940 --> 00:09:22.060
<v Speaker 1>Preparare.

00:09:22.060 --> 00:09:24.300
<v Speaker 1>What was to wait or to hope?

00:09:24.780 --> 00:09:25.820
<v Speaker 2>Esperar.

00:09:25.820 --> 00:09:26.700
<v Speaker 1>Esperar.

00:09:26.700 --> 00:09:28.140
<v Speaker 1>I will wait

00:09:29.300 --> 00:09:30.500
<v Speaker 2>Esperare.

00:09:30.500 --> 00:09:30.980
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:09:30.980 --> 00:09:34.500
<v Speaker 1>What was to organize?

00:09:34.500 --> 00:09:35.860
<v Speaker 2>Organizar.

00:09:35.860 --> 00:09:36.580
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:09:36.580 --> 00:09:38.340
<v Speaker 1>He will organize

00:09:38.940 --> 00:09:40.459
<v Speaker 2>Organisara.

00:09:40.459 --> 00:09:40.940
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:09:40.940 --> 00:09:42.459
<v Speaker 1>Organizará.

00:09:42.459 --> 00:09:50.779
<v Speaker 1>So the useful thing about the accent being on descending is that we don't have to worry about where the accent goes when we're pronouncing the whole verb.

00:09:50.579 --> 00:09:53.459
<v Speaker 1>Organisara on the end.

00:09:53.459 --> 00:09:54.819
<v Speaker 1>Organisara.

00:09:54.819 --> 00:09:57.380
<v Speaker 1>They were organized.

00:09:57.380 --> 00:09:58.819
<v Speaker 1>Organisaran.

00:09:58.819 --> 00:09:59.459
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:09:59.459 --> 00:10:00.740
<v Speaker 1>Organisaran.

00:10:00.740 --> 00:10:01.459
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:10:01.459 --> 00:10:03.540
<v Speaker 1>What was tired?

00:10:04.040 --> 00:10:05.160
<v Speaker 2>Cansado.

00:10:05.160 --> 00:10:05.880
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:10:05.880 --> 00:10:07.080
<v Speaker 1>Cansado.

00:10:07.080 --> 00:10:10.040
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say I will be tired?

00:10:10.040 --> 00:10:12.120
<v Speaker 1>I will be tired.

00:10:12.860 --> 00:10:16.780
<v Speaker 2>Sere a estaré cansada.

00:10:19.500 --> 00:10:20.140
<v Speaker 1>Good

00:10:20.720 --> 00:10:24.240
<v Speaker 1>How would it will be be from ser?

00:10:24.240 --> 00:10:27.440
<v Speaker 1>It will be using ser.

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:28.400
<v Speaker 2>Serra.

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:28.800
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:30.160
<v Speaker 1>It sound familiar from anywhere?

00:10:31.040 --> 00:10:31.600
<v Speaker 1>Serra.

00:10:31.600 --> 00:10:32.320
<v Speaker 2>Yes.

00:10:33.920 --> 00:10:36.000
<v Speaker 1>So very simple the future tense.

00:10:36.080 --> 00:10:44.480
<v Speaker 1>Doesn't matter if we have ar, er or ear verb, we are adding on these endings and these endings are the same as the different versions of aberr.

00:10:44.560 --> 00:10:47.360
<v Speaker 1>So if we forget them we can look back.

00:10:46.459 --> 00:10:49.180
<v Speaker 1>Tu haber and then we just had that on the end.

00:10:49.180 --> 00:10:54.220
<v Speaker 1>But in saying that the future tense is not so often used in Spanish

00:10:54.440 --> 00:11:02.600
<v Speaker 3>Most of the time you will find yourself using present or boy a bamos a but the future tense does exist and now you know it

